SIMPLE: winning
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Winning
<hw>Win"ning</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Attracting; adapted
to gain favor; charming; <as>as, a <ex>winning</ex> address</as>.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧Each mild and <xex>winning</xex> note.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Keble.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Winning</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Winning
<hw>Win"ning</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of obtaining
something, as in a contest or by competition.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The money, etc., gained by success in competition or
contest, esp, in gambling; -- usually in the plural.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ye seek land and sea for your <qex>winnings</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mining)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A new
opening.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The portion of a coal field out for
working.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Winning headway</b></col> <fld>(Mining)</fld>, <cd>an
excavation for exploration, in post-and-stall working.</cd> --
<col><b>Winning post</b></col>, <cd>the post, or goal, at the end of a
race.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Winningly</ent>⟦br⟧
